msgctxt "an5.209:0.2"
msgid "21. Kimilavagga "
msgstr "21. With Kimbila "

#. HTML: </p><h1>
msgctxt "an5.209:0.3"
msgid "209. Gītassarasutta "
msgstr "209. The Sound of Singing "

# NOTE: I’m not sure why BB is coy about using “singing” here, preferring “song-like intonation”. The term occurs in DN 21, where it clearly means the “sound of singing” as opposed to tantissara, the “sound of lute strings”. The text itself makes it clear it is singing “just like laypeople”.
#. HTML: </h1></div><p>
#. REF: pts-pli-vp3.251, sc1
msgctxt "an5.209:1.1"
msgid "“Pañcime, bhikkhave, ādīnavā āyatakena gītassarena dhammaṃ bhaṇantassa. "
msgstr "“Mendicants, there are these five drawbacks in reciting with a drawn-out singing sound. "

msgctxt "an5.209:1.2"
msgid "Katame pañca? "
msgstr "What five? "

msgctxt "an5.209:1.3"
msgid "Attanāpi tasmiṃ sare sārajjati, parepi tasmiṃ sare sārajjanti, gahapatikāpi ujjhāyanti: "
msgstr "You relish the sound of your own voice. Others relish the sound of your voice. Householders complain: "

msgctxt "an5.209:1.4"
msgid "‘yatheva mayaṃ gāyāma, evamevaṃ kho samaṇā sakyaputtiyā gāyantī’ti, sarakuttimpi nikāmayamānassa samādhissa bhaṅgo hoti, pacchimā janatā diṭṭhānugatiṃ āpajjati. "
msgstr "‘These ascetics, followers of the Sakyan, sing just like us!’ When you’re enjoying the melody, your immersion breaks up. Those who come after follow your example. "

msgctxt "an5.209:1.5"
msgid "Ime kho, bhikkhave, pañca ādīnavā āyatakena gītassarena dhammaṃ bhaṇantassā”ti. "
msgstr "These are the five drawbacks in reciting with a drawn-out singing sound.” "

#. HTML: </p><p class="endsection">
msgctxt "an5.209:1.6"
msgid "Navamaṃ. "
msgstr ""

